00:25.100 --> 00:30.660
chapter 1 history one day I was sitting in a

00:30.660 --> 00:33.700
cafe in Amsterdam drinking coffee and checking

00:33.700 --> 00:36.880
my map a young man was sitting at a table

00:36.880 --> 00:40.820
near me I noticed he had an unusual and interesting

00:40.820 --> 00:45.020
tattoo on his left arm it was a beautiful big

00:45.020 --> 00:48.480
red dragon the man saw me looking at his arm

00:48.480 --> 00:53.900
and smiled a gahi aun he said I'm sorry I

00:53.900 --> 00:57.120
don't speak Dutch I said to him I'm a Canadian

00:57.120 --> 00:57.720
student

00:57.720 --> 01:01.580
and I'm only here for a month the man laughed

01:01.580 --> 01:05.620
and said I was speaking Welsh not Dutch I just

01:05.620 --> 01:05.940
asked

01:05.940 --> 01:08.940
you if you are okay I saw you looking at

01:08.940 --> 01:12.380
my tattoo of the Welsh dragon so I thought you

01:12.380 --> 01:12.620
were a

01:12.620 --> 01:17.400
Welsh tourist like me you were speaking Welsh I exclaimed

01:17.400 --> 01:20.260
do people really speak Welsh today

01:21.140 --> 01:25.100
of course they speak it all over Wales be laughed

01:25.100 --> 01:27.680
don't you know anything about Wales

01:28.080 --> 01:34.920
are rugby are castles Welsh music Welsh love spoons what

01:34.920 --> 01:38.240
are love spoons I thought perhaps I

01:38.240 --> 01:43.180
just didn't understand his accent is Wales an independent country

01:43.180 --> 01:45.840
from England I asked there's

01:45.840 --> 01:49.660
no physical border or anything between them is there the

01:49.660 --> 01:54.980
man laughed of course not he said look I'm

01:54.980 --> 01:58.840
Owen and I'm also a student let's get another coffee

01:58.840 --> 02:01.500
and if you're interested I'll tell you a

02:01.500 --> 02:06.700
little about Wales what's your name I'm Ben I replied

02:06.700 --> 02:10.480
feeling very ignorant and yes I'd really

02:10.480 --> 02:14.160
like to know more about Wales he ordered us both

02:14.160 --> 02:17.000
two more coffees and began his explanation

02:18.120 --> 02:23.760
early history well Ben the history of Wales is a

02:23.760 --> 02:26.720
history of battles against all kinds of invaders

02:26.720 --> 02:31.580
in fact Wales has got more castles than any other

02:31.580 --> 02:35.080
country in Europe that's because each new

02:35.080 --> 02:39.300
invader built a castle to control the local population and

02:39.300 --> 02:42.420
prevent another invasion the first

02:42.420 --> 02:45.880
settlers came to Wales from other parts of Britain and

02:45.880 --> 02:48.020
Europe with the Celtic invasions

02:48.020 --> 02:54.280
about 700 BC then the Romans invaded Wales but they

02:54.280 --> 02:56.340
mainly used it for military purposes

02:56.340 --> 03:02.200
like forts camps and military roads when William the conqueror

03:02.200 --> 03:12.000
invaded England in 1066 he didn't intend

03:12.000 --> 03:17.600
into Wales to take control there by 1094 Williams elder

03:17.600 --> 03:19.820
son controlled most of Wales

03:20.610 --> 03:24.400
however the Welsh didn't welcome the Normans and the fighting

03:24.400 --> 03:26.180
continued for many years

03:27.260 --> 03:32.460
the situation got really bad for Wales in 1272 when

03:32.460 --> 03:34.480
King Henry III of England died

03:34.480 --> 03:38.600
and his son Edward I became the new king of

03:38.600 --> 03:41.660
England he didn't like the Welsh much

03:42.000 --> 03:46.260
and he was a strong military leader although Edward I

03:46.260 --> 03:48.340
found resistance from some great

03:48.340 --> 03:53.200
Welsh leaders he conquered Wales very easily he led three

03:53.200 --> 03:55.180
major campaigns against the Welsh

03:55.510 --> 03:59.500
and after each victory he built stone castles to defend

03:59.500 --> 04:00.300
his territories

04:01.070 --> 04:06.600
like Conway castle and Canarvon castle do these castles still

04:06.600 --> 04:08.200
exist today I asked

04:08.640 --> 04:13.940
oh yes said Owen they're very popular tourist sites some

04:13.940 --> 04:16.220
couples have their weddings inside

04:16.220 --> 04:21.860
Canarvon castle because it's a very romantic place English colonization

04:21.860 --> 04:24.100
and Welsh rebellions

04:25.060 --> 04:31.140
anyway from 1277 to 1283 Edward I began an English

04:31.140 --> 04:33.600
colonization in Wales and created

04:33.950 --> 04:38.360
many new towns Welsh peasants were forced to leave their

04:38.360 --> 04:40.680
homes and land and English peasants

04:40.680 --> 04:46.880
moved there instead however the Welsh rebellions didn't stop one

04:46.880 --> 04:48.900
of the great Welsh heroes was

04:48.900 --> 04:53.200
Owen Glindour the last native Welshmen to have the title

04:53.200 --> 04:56.680
Prince of Wales he fought fiercely and

04:56.680 --> 05:01.280
bravely for Welsh independence against English oppression but the English

05:01.280 --> 05:02.340
forces were stronger

05:02.340 --> 05:07.960
than his Welsh discontent continue throughout the centuries and the

05:07.960 --> 05:09.900
last major Welsh rebellions

05:09.900 --> 05:16.580
for independence occurred from 1400 to 1415 finally during the

05:16.580 --> 05:18.080
reign of Henry VIII of England

05:18.080 --> 05:22.880
the laws of Wales acts were passed in 1535 and

05:22.880 --> 05:28.300
1542 these acts finally made Wales an equal part

05:28.300 --> 05:32.560
of England with the same legal rights the idea was

05:32.560 --> 05:35.980
to create one single state and to put an end

05:35.980 --> 05:39.780
to the terrible battles and bloodshed between the English and

05:39.780 --> 05:40.120
the Welsh

05:41.440 --> 05:46.920
Welsh independence so do Welsh people today see themselves as

05:46.920 --> 05:49.040
English or Welsh I asked

05:49.660 --> 05:53.880
that's a good question and difficult to answer smiled Owen

05:53.880 --> 05:56.160
there are no more battles between

05:56.160 --> 05:59.280
the English and the Welsh but the desire for independence

05:59.280 --> 06:01.440
is still an important issue for

06:01.440 --> 06:06.260
many Welsh people in the 19th and 20th centuries the

06:06.260 --> 06:09.680
movement for home rule appeared and in 1925

06:10.320 --> 06:15.340
plied company the Welsh nationalist party was established now Wales

06:15.340 --> 06:16.860
has got a national assembly

06:16.860 --> 06:20.860
which decides on issues concerning Wales and the Welsh language

06:20.860 --> 06:22.280
is still widely spoken

06:22.280 --> 06:25.680
in most parts of the country how do you remember

06:25.680 --> 06:28.560
all these facts and figures Owen I asked

06:28.560 --> 06:33.760
you're like a walking encyclopedia my girlfriend says that too

06:33.760 --> 06:36.940
laughed Owen I just remember historical

06:36.940 --> 06:42.420
facts but I always forget birthdays and anniversaries so don't

06:42.420 --> 06:43.300
get too impressed

06:45.280 --> 06:51.640
chapter two geography Owen finished his coffee and looked at

06:51.640 --> 06:52.040
his watch

06:52.760 --> 06:55.700
I must go now Ben but we could meet later

06:55.700 --> 07:00.220
for a drink say around seven yes that sounds great

07:00.220 --> 07:04.720
I said see you later Owen after he left I

07:04.720 --> 07:07.900
decided to google Wales and see how big it was

07:08.480 --> 07:11.180
I looked at it on the map it seemed very

07:11.180 --> 07:14.960
small to me I started to read about the geography

07:14.960 --> 07:15.320
of the

07:15.320 --> 07:22.500
country overview Wales has got England on its eastern side

07:22.500 --> 07:24.940
and see on all the other sides

07:25.720 --> 07:28.860
it's a small country but it's got a very diverse

07:28.860 --> 07:32.680
and interesting landscape the Welsh coastline is

07:32.680 --> 07:37.480
very long and includes many islands there are large populated

07:37.480 --> 07:40.400
islands like Anglesey while

07:40.400 --> 07:45.520
others are small and uninhabited the beaches are very beautiful

07:45.520 --> 07:47.720
and some have got high cliffs

07:48.620 --> 07:51.580
Wales is the only country in the world with a

07:51.580 --> 07:56.600
continuous coastal path it's about 1400 kilometers

07:56.600 --> 08:01.120
long and has got magnificent views that attract walkers and

08:01.120 --> 08:03.280
cyclists from all over the world

08:06.000 --> 08:10.940
Snowden Wales is a very mountainous country especially in the

08:10.940 --> 08:12.480
north and central regions

08:13.010 --> 08:16.940
with hundreds of natural lakes and waterfalls as well as

08:16.940 --> 08:18.560
three large national parks

08:19.710 --> 08:23.620
the Welsh valleys are very famous one of the most

08:23.620 --> 08:25.820
beautiful natural sites in north Wales

08:25.820 --> 08:30.420
is Snowden the highest mountain in Wales standing at 1

08:30.420 --> 08:32.180
,085 meters

08:33.150 --> 08:38.100
it's situated in Snowdonia National Park a very popular park

08:38.100 --> 08:40.040
especially for mountain climbers

08:40.870 --> 08:42.660
if you want to get to the top of Snowden

08:42.660 --> 08:46.740
you can walk it there are six different walking routes

08:46.740 --> 08:50.680
and they vary in difficulty some on the mountains are

08:50.680 --> 08:51.680
very hard to climb

08:51.680 --> 08:55.900
like crib goch which has vertical drops on both sides

08:55.900 --> 08:58.280
if you don't want to walk to the top

08:58.280 --> 09:01.540
you can take a ski lift or the Snowden mountain

09:01.540 --> 09:05.240
railway and enjoy the views from the train windows

09:06.560 --> 09:11.140
Snowden in Welsh is called a witherva which means tomb

09:11.140 --> 09:21.560
or monument according to legend

09:21.560 --> 09:24.520
as trophies he then made a cape out of them

09:24.520 --> 09:28.380
to protect himself from the cold legend says that

09:28.380 --> 09:31.780
when King Arthur climbed to the top of Snowden he

09:31.780 --> 09:35.840
met Rita Gaur and killed him everybody loves

09:35.840 --> 09:41.440
a good legend Cardiff Cardiff is the capital city of

09:41.440 --> 09:44.320
Wales and the 10th largest city in the

09:44.320 --> 09:48.440
United Kingdom with a current inner city population of around

09:48.440 --> 09:51.120
358,400

09:52.150 --> 09:56.140
a very popular tourist destination Cardiff is known as the

09:56.140 --> 09:58.940
city of castles because it has got

09:58.940 --> 10:06.060
five different castles Cardiff was always very important strategically because

10:06.060 --> 10:07.020
of its location

10:07.020 --> 10:11.420
at the center of three rivers the river Taff the

10:11.420 --> 10:13.580
river Ili and the river Rimney

10:14.590 --> 10:18.520
governors could control trade and movement over a large area

10:18.520 --> 10:20.840
from Cardiff because of this

10:20.840 --> 10:24.660
the Romans constructed a fort there over 2,000 years

10:24.660 --> 10:27.540
ago and later the Normans built Cardiff

10:27.540 --> 10:32.940
castle on this fort this magnificent castle was renovated many

10:32.940 --> 10:34.520
times during its history

10:35.360 --> 10:38.380
visitors to the castle can still see the remains of

10:38.380 --> 10:41.540
the Roman fort as well as the secret tunnels

10:41.540 --> 10:47.060
that provided air raid shelters during World War II the

10:47.060 --> 10:49.740
writer Rold Dahl was born and lived in

10:49.740 --> 10:53.980
Cardiff his home and school are popular tourist sites today

10:53.980 --> 10:57.080
the tourists also love the port

10:57.080 --> 11:02.180
which was renovated in the 1990s and renamed Cardiff Bay

11:02.180 --> 11:06.000
this busy area is now full of shops

11:06.000 --> 11:10.480
and restaurants as well as the Senev the National Assembly

11:10.480 --> 11:13.540
of Wales and a spectacular entertainment

11:13.540 --> 11:20.580
center the Wales Millennium Center climate the climate in Wales

11:20.580 --> 11:22.400
like in the rest of the United

11:22.400 --> 11:27.560
Kingdom can change very quickly it rains a lot especially

11:27.560 --> 11:28.900
in the autumn and winter

11:29.740 --> 11:33.080
in the winter season the sea storms and strong currents

11:33.080 --> 11:36.360
cause many shipwrecks if you go diving

11:36.720 --> 11:40.320
you might find an underwater treasure or the remains of

11:40.320 --> 11:43.920
an old ship chapter three attractions

11:43.920 --> 11:50.580
the key house the key house near Conway castle in

11:50.580 --> 11:53.880
north Wales is the smallest house in Great Britain

11:53.880 --> 11:58.780
the building is 1.8 meters wide 2.5 meters

11:58.780 --> 12:04.140
deep and only 3.1 meters high thousands of tourists

12:04.140 --> 12:04.520
come

12:04.520 --> 12:07.820
here and try one by one to enter into the

12:07.820 --> 12:12.240
two little rooms of this tiny house only four people

12:12.240 --> 12:15.400
can be in the house at one time the upstairs

12:15.400 --> 12:18.880
is so small that only a bed and a bedside

12:18.880 --> 12:19.360
cupboard

12:19.360 --> 12:23.900
can fit inside a lady dressed in traditional Welsh clothes

12:23.900 --> 12:26.400
greets visitors and tells them

12:26.400 --> 12:30.060
about the history of the house the house was built

12:30.060 --> 12:32.460
in the 16th century and it was inhabited

12:32.460 --> 12:36.720
until 1900 the last person who lived in the house

12:36.720 --> 12:41.700
was a tall fisherman 1.91 meters he couldn't stand

12:41.700 --> 12:44.700
up fully in the house in the end he had

12:44.700 --> 12:48.520
to leave the house because it was declared unsuitable to

12:48.520 --> 12:54.920
live in planvar put gringith gorgerig plantissiliogh plan drop will

12:54.920 --> 12:57.680
go go go if you like the sound

12:57.680 --> 13:01.520
of Welsh and its strange spelling you should visit this

13:01.520 --> 13:03.280
village on the Isle of Anglesey

13:04.000 --> 13:08.200
don't worry about saying its name it's called planvar pg

13:08.200 --> 13:11.600
for short this long name gives the

13:11.600 --> 13:15.960
location of the village it means st mary's church in

13:15.960 --> 13:18.720
the hollow of the white hazel near a rapid

13:18.720 --> 13:21.920
world pool and the church of st to stilio of

13:21.920 --> 13:25.400
the red cave this incredible name was chosen

13:25.400 --> 13:28.260
as the name of the village in the 19th century

13:28.260 --> 13:32.520
to attract tourists today thousands of tourists take

13:32.520 --> 13:35.560
pictures by the 4.6 meter wide sign on the

13:35.560 --> 13:39.400
railway platform it's the longest name of a place in

13:39.400 --> 13:43.060
europe and of course it appears in the Guinness world

13:43.060 --> 13:46.560
of records can you imagine a small railway

13:46.560 --> 13:52.280
ticket with a 58 letter destination printed on it port

13:52.280 --> 13:56.700
marion port marion is an unusual and

13:56.700 --> 14:01.240
picturesque tourist village in north Wales it was designed by

14:01.240 --> 14:03.320
the architect saklaf williams

14:03.320 --> 14:10.040
ellis and built between the years 1925 and 1975 this

14:10.040 --> 14:12.860
is a very special place because it looks

14:12.860 --> 14:17.560
like an Italian village but in Wales every building is

14:17.560 --> 14:19.980
different in color and shape there

14:19.980 --> 14:23.380
are lots of beautiful gardens and a path leading down

14:23.380 --> 14:27.320
to the sea so klaf williams ellis was an

14:27.320 --> 14:31.860
environmentalist his plan was to build a tourist village that

14:31.860 --> 14:33.400
was an attractive place to live

14:34.080 --> 14:38.080
the village itself is not large but the architectural designs

14:38.080 --> 14:40.060
the arches and the piazza

14:40.060 --> 14:44.980
make it look bigger not surprisingly port marion is extremely

14:44.980 --> 14:46.320
popular with the tourists

14:47.820 --> 14:53.040
animal attractions you can see dolphins porpoises and seals in

14:53.040 --> 14:54.980
Wales in the spring and summer months

14:55.560 --> 14:58.440
and if you're lucky you may even see a humpback

14:58.440 --> 15:01.400
whale and of course there are sheep

15:02.020 --> 15:04.980
in fact there are more sheep than people in Wales

15:04.980 --> 15:07.900
they're a major part of the Welsh landscape

15:08.560 --> 15:11.760
walking around the hills and mountains and they're not frightened

15:11.760 --> 15:13.940
of cars so they often appear

15:13.940 --> 15:19.740
in the middle of country roads birds there are many

15:19.740 --> 15:21.100
interesting birds in Wales

15:21.100 --> 15:25.060
and the most famous one is the red kite once

15:25.060 --> 15:27.920
this bird of prey was in danger of extinction

15:28.740 --> 15:32.680
but because of intense conservation efforts it has survived and

15:32.680 --> 15:34.340
you can see it in many parts of

15:34.340 --> 15:38.540
Wales in fact there are so many red kites that

15:38.540 --> 15:41.280
it is often regarded as the unofficial national

15:41.280 --> 15:45.420
bird of Wales the best place to see red kites

15:45.420 --> 15:49.340
is midwales it's a truly wonderful sight

15:49.920 --> 15:53.960
watching these elegant birds flying in the sky they've got

15:53.960 --> 15:56.180
beautiful long wings and a long tail

15:56.970 --> 16:01.180
they mainly eat small mammals like rabbits and mice but

16:01.180 --> 16:03.580
they also enjoy feeding on a carcass

16:03.580 --> 16:07.080
there are even special farms where tourists can watch them

16:07.080 --> 16:10.200
feed the big pit national coal museum

16:11.280 --> 16:15.440
during the 19th and 20th centuries coal and slate mining

16:15.440 --> 16:17.500
were major industries in Wales

16:18.480 --> 16:21.640
Cardiff was one of the largest coal exporting ports in

16:21.640 --> 16:22.040
the world

16:22.580 --> 16:26.640
both industries still exist today but on a much smaller

16:26.640 --> 16:30.360
scale in the past the coal and slate

16:30.360 --> 16:35.480
mines provided work for adults and for children some children

16:35.480 --> 16:37.300
started to work in the mines when

16:37.300 --> 16:41.340
they were only 60 years old like their parents they

16:41.340 --> 16:44.080
worked long hours in dangerous uncomfortable

16:44.080 --> 16:49.160
and badly ventilated conditions there were many accidents where miners

16:49.160 --> 16:51.060
were killed or badly hurt

16:51.060 --> 16:55.000
the big pit national coal museum in Blanavon south Wales

16:55.000 --> 16:57.560
is one of the few remaining mines

16:57.560 --> 17:01.600
where visitors can tour 90 meters below the ground and

17:01.600 --> 17:03.100
learn about life in the mines

17:03.900 --> 17:08.300
around 140 000 tourists visit it every year

17:09.220 --> 17:15.960
chapter four traditional food and drink traditional Welsh food is

17:15.960 --> 17:16.660
quite simple

17:16.660 --> 17:20.680
and represents the lives of the working people since many

17:20.680 --> 17:22.720
Welsh people lived in remote areas

17:23.080 --> 17:26.780
they had to cook using ingredients that were available and

17:26.780 --> 17:27.360
economical

17:28.700 --> 17:32.680
vegetables came from the garden or local farms the fish

17:32.680 --> 17:34.580
from the rivers lakes or the sea

17:35.150 --> 17:38.920
and the meat usually came from the family pig although

17:38.920 --> 17:41.160
lamb is a popular meat in Wales today

17:41.570 --> 17:44.840
in the past it was only eaten on special days

17:44.840 --> 17:48.240
or holidays historically there were no written

17:48.240 --> 17:53.560
recipes recipes were passed down orally from generation to generation

17:55.600 --> 18:00.180
call call is a traditional Welsh soup and is often

18:00.180 --> 18:02.120
considered the national dish of Wales

18:03.060 --> 18:06.720
it's a winter dish that originated in the 14th century

18:06.720 --> 18:09.340
once it was made with bacon

18:09.340 --> 18:14.680
or beef together with vegetables like carrots or potatoes today

18:14.680 --> 18:17.020
call is often made with lamb

18:17.020 --> 18:23.460
and leak lava bread lava bread is a traditional Welsh

18:23.460 --> 18:26.620
dish made from lava an edible seaweed

18:26.620 --> 18:30.460
found on the rocks along the coastline of Wales it's

18:30.460 --> 18:32.380
extremely nutritious because it's

18:32.380 --> 18:36.480
rich in minerals proteins and vitamins the lava is cooked

18:36.480 --> 18:39.060
for hours and then made into a greenish

18:39.060 --> 18:44.280
black puree or paste a traditional Welsh breakfast usually consists

18:44.280 --> 18:45.260
of lava bread

18:45.260 --> 18:50.260
bacon sausage eggs and cockles some people use lava as

18:50.260 --> 18:52.100
sauce or make it into soup

18:52.860 --> 18:56.780
during the 18th century lava was a basic and important

18:56.780 --> 18:58.060
food for the miners

18:59.060 --> 19:01.920
the miners wives collected it from the rocks on the

19:01.920 --> 19:04.340
coast and either sold it in the market

19:04.340 --> 19:09.200
or prepared lava bread with it a typical miner started

19:09.200 --> 19:12.340
his day with lava bread as part of his

19:12.340 --> 19:16.960
traditional Welsh breakfast although the production of lava has become

19:16.960 --> 19:17.440
industrialized

19:18.470 --> 19:21.860
the traditional methods of preparing it still remain in some

19:21.860 --> 19:23.120
parts of Wales today

19:24.080 --> 19:29.480
glamorgan sausage the glamorgan sausage is different from regular sausages

19:29.480 --> 19:30.340
because it's

19:30.340 --> 19:35.800
completely vegetarian it's traditionally made with a white Welsh cheese

19:35.800 --> 19:38.040
called kafili leak

19:38.040 --> 19:42.920
and breadcrumbs these sausages were particularly popular during world war

19:42.920 --> 19:43.260
two

19:43.820 --> 19:46.060
when it was hard to find meat to buy.

19:47.840 --> 19:48.640
Barra brief

19:49.840 --> 19:57.680
Barra means bread and brief means speckled. So barra brief literally means speckled bread.

19:58.560 --> 20:01.440
It is a cake with dried fruit and spices.

20:02.320 --> 20:05.040
Barra brief is served with butter at tea time.

20:05.680 --> 20:11.120
In fact, in Argentina, there's a kind of barra brief called torta negra.

20:12.080 --> 20:16.400
This comes from the Welsh settlers who brought their traditional dishes with them

20:16.400 --> 20:22.800
when they arrived in Patagonia, and it still served today in Welsh tea houses in that area.

20:24.640 --> 20:25.120
Drinks

20:25.760 --> 20:28.720
Wales produces beer, whiskey and wine.

20:29.360 --> 20:33.840
A popular new kind of gin called seaweed gin is made in Wales.

20:34.480 --> 20:39.840
It's made with seaweed from the Welsh coast and is processed at a local distillery.

20:40.640 --> 20:43.760
The colour and taste of the seaweed depends on the season,

20:44.480 --> 20:46.800
and this influences the taste of the gin.

20:47.680 --> 20:53.920
The seaweed makes the gin a bit salty, but it's got a very distinct and unique taste.

20:55.360 --> 20:56.400
Chapter 5

20:57.120 --> 20:58.960
Festivals and Traditions

21:00.480 --> 21:01.600
St David's Day

21:02.160 --> 21:06.240
The most famous national holiday in Wales is St David's Day.

21:06.800 --> 21:10.880
On the 1st of March, there are lots of celebrations on this day.

21:11.440 --> 21:15.440
Traditional songs are sung and traditional food is eaten.

21:15.440 --> 21:21.520
Some children dress in the Welsh national costume and hold leeks and daffodils too.

21:21.520 --> 21:24.160
St David is the patron saint of Wales.

21:24.880 --> 21:30.000
He was born about 1500 years ago and he was educated at a monastery.

21:31.120 --> 21:32.560
Later he became a monk.

21:33.440 --> 21:37.760
According to legend, St David performed many miracles in his life.

21:38.640 --> 21:44.400
People believe that he helped a blind man to see again and brought a child back to life

21:44.400 --> 21:46.320
by wetting him with his tears.

21:47.360 --> 21:53.280
However, according to legend, his most famous miracle was when he was giving a sermon to a

21:53.280 --> 21:57.360
large number of people and many couldn't see or hear him.

21:58.000 --> 22:04.400
Then a white dove landed on David's shoulder and the ground that David was standing on

22:04.400 --> 22:06.080
rose up to a large hill.

22:06.800 --> 22:09.920
Suddenly everybody could see and hear him.

22:09.920 --> 22:16.240
A church was built on this hill with pictures and stained glass windows showing St David

22:16.240 --> 22:18.720
with the white dove on his shoulder.

22:18.720 --> 22:22.800
To this day, the white dove is the emblem of St David.

22:23.360 --> 22:28.720
There are many churches and chapels in St David's name as well as a flag.

22:28.720 --> 22:34.800
The name Davith is the Welsh name for David and many boys in Wales are called that.

22:36.560 --> 22:38.000
St Dewin Wednesday.

22:38.560 --> 22:46.000
On the 25th of January, the Welsh celebrate St Dewin Wednesday which is a romantic day

22:46.000 --> 22:46.640
for lovers.

22:47.200 --> 22:51.760
People exchange cards and they are celebrations all over Wales.

22:52.320 --> 22:55.360
Dewin Wenn is the Welsh patron saint of lovers.

22:55.920 --> 23:02.880
In the 5th century, there was a king called Brechann Brechanyog who had 24 daughters.

23:02.880 --> 23:05.040
Dewin Wenn was the most beautiful.

23:05.840 --> 23:12.080
She was in love with a man called Mylon but her father had a different man for her to marry.

23:12.080 --> 23:17.360
Dewin Wenn was sad and asked God to help her forget Mylon.

23:17.440 --> 23:23.120
That night, an angel visited Dewin Wenn in her sleep and gave her a sweet potion.

23:24.000 --> 23:29.120
This helped her forget her feelings for Mylon and turned him into a block of ice.

23:29.840 --> 23:32.160
God then gave Dewin Wenn three wishes.

23:32.800 --> 23:36.160
Her first wish was for Mylon to be thawed.

23:36.160 --> 23:42.960
Her second wish was for God to help all lovers and her final wish was that she would never marry.

23:43.440 --> 23:46.080
God answered all three wishes.

23:46.080 --> 23:51.200
In return, Dewin Wenn became a nun and dedicated her life to God.

23:51.200 --> 23:55.840
She built the church of St. Dewin Wenn and founded a convent on the island

23:55.840 --> 23:58.240
of Flangthwin near Anglesey.

23:58.240 --> 24:02.880
The remains of the church and Dewin Wenn's well can be seen on the island.

24:02.880 --> 24:07.120
The well is still a favorite place for young Welsh lovers even today.

24:07.120 --> 24:16.000
I stethvoth meaning sitting together or gathering is a Welsh festival of music,

24:16.000 --> 24:17.520
literature and performance.

24:18.320 --> 24:21.840
The first I stethvoth took place in the 12th century.

24:22.640 --> 24:29.360
Poets and musicians from all over Wales were invited to recite their poetry or play their music

24:29.360 --> 24:31.520
and judges chose the best one.

24:32.320 --> 24:36.240
An elegant high-backed chair with arms was awarded to the winner.

24:37.200 --> 24:43.120
This was a prestigious prize because from the medieval period until the 1700s,

24:43.680 --> 24:46.240
ordinary people sat on simple stools.

24:47.200 --> 24:51.920
High-backed chairs were kept for royalty and people of high status only.

24:52.560 --> 24:58.160
Today, the nationalized stethvoth of Wales takes place every August for eight days

24:58.160 --> 25:02.240
and it's the largest festival of poetry and music in Europe.

25:02.240 --> 25:05.120
The entire competition is held in Welsh.

25:05.840 --> 25:08.720
Chapter 6. Language

25:10.480 --> 25:16.480
I met Owen later that evening and we decided to tour together over the following days.

25:17.520 --> 25:20.720
I know all about Wales now, I told him.

25:20.720 --> 25:25.280
I spent an hour googling all sorts of interesting things about your country.

25:26.240 --> 25:30.160
Next time I go to the UK, I'll include Wales in the trip.

25:31.120 --> 25:33.760
Good idea, Ben, said Owen.

25:33.760 --> 25:38.400
I'll show you lots of cool places, but I'm not speaking Welsh.

25:38.400 --> 25:40.240
It's such a hard language.

25:40.240 --> 25:43.200
You said a lot of people speak Welsh today, Owen.

25:43.200 --> 25:46.000
But what do you usually speak at home, I asked?

25:46.000 --> 25:47.840
Welsh or English?

25:47.840 --> 25:51.520
Why speak Welsh most of the time, answered Owen?

25:52.240 --> 25:55.680
I speak it at work with my friends and with my family.

25:56.400 --> 25:58.320
Really, I said surprised.

25:58.960 --> 26:03.520
Before I met you, I thought Welsh was a dead language, like Latin.

26:04.320 --> 26:06.160
Absolutely not.

26:06.160 --> 26:08.240
Most people can speak and write Welsh.

26:09.040 --> 26:12.640
It's an obligatory subject in all schools until the age of 16.

26:13.600 --> 26:16.960
Children learn it as either a first or second language.

26:17.600 --> 26:21.680
In fact, quite a lot of children are taught all their subjects in Welsh.

26:22.480 --> 26:26.080
When you come to Wales, you'll see and hear Welsh everywhere.

26:26.720 --> 26:31.200
There are radio stations and a TV channel with all their programs in Welsh.

26:31.840 --> 26:34.720
Also, there are Welsh newspapers and magazines,

26:35.280 --> 26:37.760
and the road signs are in both languages.

26:38.480 --> 26:41.120
Welsh is really Britain's oldest language.

26:41.680 --> 26:44.720
The Romans were the first people to write in Welsh,

26:44.720 --> 26:46.960
and there are elements of Latin in the language.

26:47.680 --> 26:52.160
From the 7th century, the people of Wales were called Commeri,

26:52.240 --> 26:56.640
which means Welsh, and Wales created its own laws in Welsh.

26:57.360 --> 27:00.160
But the Welsh language has also had its battles.

27:00.800 --> 27:07.440
In 1536, Henry VIII passed a law, which prohibited using Welsh in the legal system

27:07.440 --> 27:09.360
and in administrative affairs.

27:10.320 --> 27:15.600
Then in 1549, the English Parliament passed the Act of Uniformity,

27:15.600 --> 27:19.440
which said all public prayer had to be in English.

27:20.400 --> 27:28.000
Fortunately for us, in 1563, Queen Elizabeth I allowed the Bible and the prayer book

27:28.000 --> 27:31.520
to be printed in Welsh, and this brought the language back again.

27:32.320 --> 27:34.800
Welsh people went to church regularly,

27:34.800 --> 27:37.520
so the translations helped the language survive.

27:38.320 --> 27:44.080
Welsh literature, especially poetry, has helped to preserve the language and national identity.

27:44.960 --> 27:48.480
In 1870, the English Act of Education

27:48.480 --> 27:51.840
made English the official language of instruction at schools,

27:52.480 --> 27:54.560
to put an end to the Welsh language.

27:55.520 --> 27:57.840
Children who spoke Welsh were punished.

27:58.400 --> 28:01.120
If a teacher heard a child speaking Welsh,

28:01.120 --> 28:05.040
he would put a Welsh knot sign around the child's neck.

28:05.840 --> 28:09.200
Even the names of towns were changed into English.

28:09.200 --> 28:13.040
For example, Khairdiv became Cardiff.

28:13.840 --> 28:17.280
So, how has the language survived until now, Owen?

28:17.280 --> 28:17.920
I asked.

28:18.880 --> 28:22.960
Well, a sense of national identity has led to the revival of the language.

28:23.600 --> 28:27.760
Now there's Welsh language instruction in schools, education centres,

28:27.760 --> 28:30.880
and on Welsh radio stations and TV channels.

28:31.920 --> 28:34.560
Ben, have you heard of Patagonia?

28:35.520 --> 28:37.440
That's in South America, isn't it?

28:37.440 --> 28:38.080
I asked.

28:38.720 --> 28:41.440
Yes, in Argentina, Owen answered.

28:42.080 --> 28:47.600
In 1865, several Welsh people arrived in Patagonia and stayed there.

28:48.160 --> 28:51.920
They wanted to keep their culture and language, so they spoke Welsh.

28:52.640 --> 28:56.640
Then more Welsh people started to visit the region in the 60s,

28:56.640 --> 28:58.400
and this revived the language.

28:59.040 --> 29:03.360
Today they still speak Patagonia and Welsh there, a dialect of Welsh.

29:04.000 --> 29:08.640
Welsh teachers are sent to Patagonia to instruct local teachers in the language.

29:09.360 --> 29:13.680
Apparently speaking Welsh is a sign of prestige in Patagonia.

29:14.560 --> 29:16.880
Can you understand Patagonian Welsh?

29:16.880 --> 29:17.520
I asked.

29:18.080 --> 29:19.760
Oh yes, said Owen.

29:19.760 --> 29:21.680
It's not so different from our Welsh.

29:22.400 --> 29:25.600
Owen lifted his cup of coffee, looked at me and said,

29:25.600 --> 29:28.160
Comery ambeath.

29:29.440 --> 29:31.680
I tried unsuccessfully to repeat that.

29:32.400 --> 29:34.080
What does it mean, I asked?

29:34.960 --> 29:39.520
Wales forever, smiled Owen, and drank some more coffee.

29:40.640 --> 29:44.320
Chapter 7 Sport Rugby

29:46.000 --> 29:49.200
Wales participates in many world sporting events,

29:49.920 --> 29:53.040
like the Rugby World Cup and the FIFA World Cup.

29:53.840 --> 29:56.240
Although the Welsh like playing football,

29:56.240 --> 29:59.920
the sport that most people associate with Wales is rugby.

30:01.120 --> 30:06.160
Rugby is considered the national sport and it's played and followed throughout Wales.

30:07.040 --> 30:12.560
The Welsh Rugby Union, WRU, supervises the different rugby clubs,

30:12.560 --> 30:16.000
the national team, the referees, players and trainers.

30:16.960 --> 30:18.480
Rugby isn't just for men.

30:19.280 --> 30:21.760
There's a WRU team for women too.

30:22.560 --> 30:25.120
Both teams have got the same emblem.

30:25.120 --> 30:30.160
The Prince of Wales is feathers and they both wear the same uniform,

30:30.160 --> 30:33.360
red shirts, white shorts and red socks.

30:34.480 --> 30:38.640
At every game, the enthusiastic fans sing Welsh rugby songs.

30:39.360 --> 30:41.680
These are often folk songs or hymns.

30:42.240 --> 30:46.240
In fact, some of these religious songs were sung in the late 19th century.

30:47.040 --> 30:50.160
The oldest Welsh rugby song is Men of Harlech,

30:50.720 --> 30:54.640
which is about Welsh resistance during the siege of Harlech Castle,

30:55.520 --> 30:58.800
between 1461 and 1468.

31:00.080 --> 31:01.440
The Millennium Stadium

31:02.560 --> 31:03.920
The Millennium Stadium

31:04.960 --> 31:09.920
The Millennium Stadium, recently renamed the Principality Stadium,

31:09.920 --> 31:14.640
opened in June 1999 and it's the biggest arena in Wales.

31:15.360 --> 31:21.360
It's got a retractable roof and it can seat 74,500 visitors.

31:22.480 --> 31:26.960
At international rugby games, the Welsh fans stand in the stadium,

31:26.960 --> 31:29.760
all loudly saying their national anthem,

31:29.760 --> 31:33.200
Land of My Fathers, Hayne Vlada-Nadhi.

31:34.080 --> 31:36.640
Besides the National Rugby Union team,

31:36.640 --> 31:40.320
the stadium also hosts the Welsh national football team

31:40.320 --> 31:42.640
and has had music concerts there,

31:42.640 --> 31:46.560
including Madonna, U2 and Red Hot Chili Peppers.

31:48.240 --> 31:48.800
Jousting

31:50.000 --> 31:53.840
In medieval times, the most popular Welsh sport was Jousting.

31:54.800 --> 31:58.960
Wales is a country of castles and Jousting was once the favourite

31:58.960 --> 32:02.400
form of entertainment of kings, knights and noblemen.

32:03.440 --> 32:07.840
Two knights fought on horseback and the objective was to break the lands

32:07.840 --> 32:12.240
on his opponent's armour or shield and to make him fall from his horse.

32:13.200 --> 32:15.520
It was a battle of speed and courage.

32:16.320 --> 32:20.160
In medieval times, the winning jouster was given a prize

32:20.160 --> 32:23.760
like a gold ring, a sword or an elaborate helmet,

32:24.480 --> 32:26.400
but the loser often died.

32:27.120 --> 32:29.280
Jousting was a dangerous sport.

32:30.320 --> 32:33.920
Every year in June, Cardiff Castle has a medieval weekend,

32:34.560 --> 32:36.800
with traditional jousting for the visitors.

32:37.440 --> 32:40.640
Even today, they are riding schools that teach Jousting.

32:41.280 --> 32:44.480
The sport requires control and physical strength

32:44.480 --> 32:48.160
because the armour is made of steel, which makes it very heavy.

32:49.120 --> 32:53.280
Jousters must train daily and must also be good at horse riding

32:53.280 --> 32:56.640
and have good balance because they need to hold a long

32:56.640 --> 32:58.560
land in one hand while riding.

32:59.200 --> 33:01.200
That's not so easy at all.

33:02.000 --> 33:02.800
Chapter 8

33:03.840 --> 33:04.800
Famous figures

33:04.800 --> 33:07.600
Owen Glendour

33:09.360 --> 33:12.640
One of the greatest Welsh heroes was Owen Glendour.

33:13.200 --> 33:17.520
He was the last native Welshman to have the title Prince of Wales.

33:18.080 --> 33:22.480
Owen was a strong charismatic leader who united and led the Welsh

33:22.480 --> 33:24.880
against the English in the 14th century.

33:25.680 --> 33:30.080
Welshman from all social classes joined Owen in his revolt

33:30.080 --> 33:33.840
and supported his desire for Welsh independence from England.

33:33.840 --> 33:38.960
After years of fighting, the revolt ended and by 1410,

33:38.960 --> 33:40.960
Owen was a wanted fugitive.

33:41.600 --> 33:47.520
No one knows exactly when he died, but his memory remains strong throughout Wales

33:48.160 --> 33:50.800
and many parks and streets have his name.

33:52.880 --> 33:53.760
Dylan Thomas

33:54.960 --> 34:01.680
Popular Welsh poet Dylan Thomas is probably one of the most important poets of the 20th century.

34:02.560 --> 34:07.600
He was born in Swansea on the southern coast of Wales in 1914.

34:08.400 --> 34:13.760
His father and English literature professor used to recite Shakespeare to Thomas,

34:13.760 --> 34:16.720
inspiring a love of literature from an early age.

34:17.680 --> 34:22.080
Much of his inspiration and ideas came from the Welsh countryside.

34:22.080 --> 34:25.200
He is famous for his collected poems of Dylan Thomas.

34:25.760 --> 34:31.760
Radio plays like Undermilkwood and a book Portrait of the Artist as a Young Dog.

34:32.640 --> 34:38.320
Surprisingly, Dylan Thomas, the most famous Welsh poet, never wrote in Welsh.

34:39.360 --> 34:43.520
Dylan Thomas died in the United States at 39 years of age

34:44.160 --> 34:49.120
and there is a plaque to his memory in Poets Corner in Westminster Abbey, London.

34:50.080 --> 34:56.080
Welsh celebrities name, birthplace, profession, achievements.

34:57.200 --> 34:58.160
Gareth Bale

34:59.200 --> 35:00.240
1989

35:00.800 --> 35:01.360
Cardiff

35:02.320 --> 35:06.960
Top footballer, plays for Real Madrid and the Welsh national team.

35:07.760 --> 35:10.720
Sir Anthony Hopkins, 1937

35:11.520 --> 35:13.440
Port Talbot, actor

35:14.400 --> 35:16.720
works in cinema, theatre and television.

35:17.280 --> 35:23.520
One Oscar for Best Actor in the Silence of the Lambs, 1991 and Two Emmys,

35:24.400 --> 35:31.920
knighted by Queen Elizabeth II in 1993, received a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame.

35:33.360 --> 35:36.160
Sir Tom Jones, 1940

35:36.960 --> 35:37.840
Ponta Prive

35:38.720 --> 35:39.120
Singer

35:39.920 --> 35:49.040
Popular Singer has sold over 100 million records as 36 top 40 hits in the UK and 19 in the United

35:49.040 --> 35:49.520
States.

35:50.640 --> 35:57.440
Received a Grammy Award and two Brit Awards, knighted by Queen Elizabeth II for services to music.

35:57.440 --> 36:03.520
Roll Dahl, 1916 to 1990

36:04.080 --> 36:04.640
Cardiff

36:05.280 --> 36:07.680
Writer, poet and screenwriter

36:08.560 --> 36:14.320
His most famous works include Charlie and the Chocolate Factory, Matilda, The Witches,

36:14.320 --> 36:22.000
Fantastic Mr. Fox and James and the Giant Peach, sold more than 250 million books worldwide

36:22.000 --> 36:25.760
and received several awards for his contribution to literature.

36:27.520 --> 36:30.720
Catherine Zeta-Jones, 1969

36:31.440 --> 36:33.200
Swansea, Actress

36:34.000 --> 36:40.960
Works in Theatre, Cinema and Television has won several awards including an Oscar for Chicago

36:40.960 --> 36:44.720
and a CBE for her film and humanitarian works.

36:45.440 --> 36:50.480
She appeared in Intorable Cruelty, The Terminal and The Legend of Zorro.

36:51.440 --> 36:52.320
Chapter 9

36:53.280 --> 36:54.560
Welsh Symbols

36:55.520 --> 36:56.080
The Flag

36:56.800 --> 37:02.240
The Welsh Flag has got two large horizontal stripes, one green and one white

37:02.960 --> 37:05.360
and a large red dragon in the middle.

37:06.560 --> 37:12.400
Green and white were the colors of the 15th century Tudor royal family who came from Wales.

37:13.360 --> 37:18.000
They added the red dragon to the Tudor flag to emphasize their Welsh descent.

37:18.880 --> 37:26.400
However, it was only in 1959 as the flag officially became the National Flag of Wales.

37:27.280 --> 37:30.720
The red dragon supposedly comes from the time of King Arthur.

37:31.520 --> 37:36.000
According to legend, the wizard Merlin had a vision of a red dragon,

37:36.640 --> 37:44.240
the native Britons, fighting a white dragon, the Saxon invaders and the red dragon won the battle.

37:45.200 --> 37:49.840
Today, the red dragon represents all things that are connected to Wales.

37:51.280 --> 37:51.840
The Leek

37:52.400 --> 37:57.280
It might surprise you to read that one of the national emblems of Wales is the Leek.

37:58.400 --> 38:04.400
According to one legend, King Cadwalader ordered his soldiers to wear a Leek on their helmets

38:04.400 --> 38:06.960
when they were fighting the Saxons in a Leek field.

38:07.920 --> 38:12.720
The Leeks helped them identify themselves and gave them good camouflage from their enemy.

38:13.280 --> 38:18.480
Another legend says that St David always ate Leeks even when he was fasting.

38:19.040 --> 38:21.040
So they became his personal symbol.

38:21.760 --> 38:28.560
Today, many Welsh people wear a Leek on St David's day to celebrate their victory against the Saxons.

38:30.400 --> 38:31.200
The Daffodil

38:32.080 --> 38:37.600
The Daffodil is another symbol of Wales, but that may be due to some language confusion.

38:38.480 --> 38:40.640
A Leek in Welsh is Ken Hinnen,

38:41.440 --> 38:46.640
and a Daffodil in Welsh is Ken Hinnen Peder, which means Peter's Leek.

38:47.520 --> 38:53.520
Daffodils are spring flowers and since St David's day is on 1st of March, many people

38:53.520 --> 38:57.920
wear a Daffodil on that day too. Traditional Welsh costume

38:59.120 --> 39:06.480
Welsh women had a traditional costume, but it was mainly poorer rural women who wore it at the market.

39:07.280 --> 39:09.760
There are many different variations of this costume,

39:10.320 --> 39:15.360
but it generally consists of a striped under dress with a shawl and an apron.

39:16.480 --> 39:20.960
And the most important part of the Welsh costume is the tall chimney hat.

39:22.240 --> 39:25.600
The Welsh costume became a symbol of national identity,

39:25.600 --> 39:31.600
and today women wear it on special occasions like St David's day or at Eistelvaz.

39:33.040 --> 39:33.920
Love spoons

39:34.000 --> 39:40.160
You can't visit a Welsh gift shop without seeing a variety of love spoons.

39:41.040 --> 39:43.920
The Welsh love spoon is a very popular souvenir.

39:44.640 --> 39:50.080
Made by hand from one piece of wood, it is carved with a special message or symbol,

39:50.080 --> 39:57.600
for example, a heart for love, a horseshoe for luck, a cross for religion, and bells for marriage.

39:58.720 --> 40:03.600
The tradition of carving and giving a love spoon to a girl originated in Wales

40:03.680 --> 40:10.640
in the 17th century. The spoons were not actually used, they were displayed as ornaments on the wall.

40:11.600 --> 40:14.960
Young men carved their love and intentions on a love spoon.

40:15.840 --> 40:20.240
If a girl kept the love spoon, it was a sign that she was interested in him.

40:20.880 --> 40:24.320
If she returned it, it was clear she didn't want the man.

40:25.280 --> 40:30.800
The love spoon tradition disappeared in the 19th century, but over the last 40 years,

40:30.800 --> 40:34.720
there's been a revival and people, especially tourists,

40:34.720 --> 40:39.280
by hand-made love spoons for their loved ones on special occasions,

40:39.280 --> 40:46.640
like anniversaries, births or graduations. It's certainly more original than a box of chocolates

40:46.640 --> 40:51.680
or flowers. Chapter 10. Myths and Legends

40:53.840 --> 41:00.560
It's not surprising that a country with so many castles has got lots of legends and ghost stories.

41:01.440 --> 41:05.600
There are plenty of stories of haunted castles and buildings in Wales.

41:06.560 --> 41:12.400
Strange things seem to happen in Cardiff Castle, particularly in its southwest corner.

41:13.360 --> 41:20.480
Apparently, at 3.45 every morning, the heavy doors of the dining room open and closed by

41:20.480 --> 41:28.000
themselves and the lights go on and off. Another scary story is the sudden appearance of the

41:28.000 --> 41:33.440
second Marquis of Bute. He lived in Cardiff Castle in the 19th century.

41:34.240 --> 41:40.080
According to some people, he sometimes appears in the library dressed in a long red coat

41:40.640 --> 41:47.920
that's enough to terrify the tourists. Another castle with a reputation for ghosts is Castle

41:47.920 --> 41:55.440
Koch, Red Castle, which is nine kilometers from Cardiff. It looks beautiful and romantic,

41:55.520 --> 42:02.480
but it's got dark dungeons and corridors. In fact, on Halloween, there are special ghost tours there.

42:03.360 --> 42:08.640
There's a legend about the Castle Koch ghost who continues to search for the treasure he hid

42:08.640 --> 42:14.720
in the walls of the castle. Some people say they experience a strange feeling in the chapel,

42:14.720 --> 42:20.560
as if someone is watching them. Some hear strange sounds in the Great Hall, and others

42:20.640 --> 42:28.000
maintain that a spirit touched them. If you're a nervous person, it's probably best not to take

42:28.000 --> 42:34.720
the Castle Koch night tour. Devil's Bridge, a village in West Wales.

42:36.560 --> 42:43.200
Another popular tourist site is a village called Ponta Finnach, which means the bridge on the

42:43.200 --> 42:50.720
Manach. This unusual bridge is actually not one bridge, but three bridges, one built on the other.

42:51.600 --> 42:57.520
The first bridge was built of stone in the 11th century, the second in 1753,

42:57.520 --> 43:03.680
and the third iron bridge in 1901. Visitors can walk down stone steps,

43:03.680 --> 43:09.440
called Jacob's Ladder, from the third bridge to the first bridge to see a beautiful waterfall.

43:10.320 --> 43:14.640
So how did this interesting feature get its name, Devil's Bridge?

43:16.160 --> 43:22.960
According to legend, the bridge was built by the devil. Apparently, in the 11th century,

43:22.960 --> 43:29.840
the devil visited Wales and met an old woman with her dog. The old woman was worried about her

43:29.840 --> 43:36.080
cow, which was trapped on the other side of the river. The devil wanted the woman's soul,

43:36.720 --> 43:42.880
so he agreed to build a bridge across the river in return for the soul of the first living thing

43:42.880 --> 43:49.920
that crossed the bridge. But the old woman was clever. As soon as the devil finished building the

43:49.920 --> 43:56.720
bridge, she threw some bread onto the bridge. Her dog ran after the bread and became the first

43:56.720 --> 44:04.160
living thing to cross the bridge. The devil was so humiliated by this that he left Wales and never

44:04.240 --> 44:07.280
returned again. King Arthur

44:08.720 --> 44:14.320
There are many legends of King Arthur and Wales. Two lakes in Snowdonia,

44:14.320 --> 44:21.680
Lake Lidor and Lake Ogwin, are both reputed to contain King Arthur's magical sword Excalibur.

44:22.640 --> 44:27.040
There are also rocks that supposedly show the hoof prints of King Arthur's horse.

44:28.000 --> 44:32.320
A stone on the banks of Lake Barfog has strange hoof prints,

44:32.960 --> 44:38.160
supposedly from the time when King Arthur and his horse pulled a monster from the lake.

44:39.360 --> 44:43.840
There are lots of fantasy tales and legends about the western coast of Wales.

44:44.560 --> 44:51.440
These remote places inspire frightening thoughts and wild imagination, which make the best ghost

44:51.440 --> 44:58.560
stories. Chapter 11 Arts Wales Land of Song

45:00.640 --> 45:08.400
Wales is known as the Land of Song, and it has got many Welsh male choirs. These originated in the

45:08.400 --> 45:15.040
19th century during the Industrial Revolution, and are an important part of Welsh culture and

45:15.040 --> 45:24.080
identity. Today there are over 100 male choirs in Wales. The industrial workforce in Wales

45:24.080 --> 45:30.320
came from the working class, and most of the workers were men. They worked long hours in the

45:30.320 --> 45:36.960
ports, mines or railways, and they often organized themselves into a local choir within their workplace.

45:38.000 --> 45:44.240
The choir was a way for them to relax after a hard day's work. It gave these hard working men

45:44.240 --> 45:50.640
a sense of identity and pride, and a unique chance to see other places in Wales and England,

45:51.280 --> 45:57.920
because choirs often competed against each other. The choirs sang mainly traditional Welsh songs

45:57.920 --> 46:05.280
and hymns, but sometimes light opera or popular modern songs. The songs were often accompanied

46:05.280 --> 46:12.480
by the triple harp, a harp with three rows of strings. This instrument was played so much in

46:12.560 --> 46:18.880
Wales that it became known as the Welsh harp. Today it's considered the natural instrument of

46:18.880 --> 46:23.520
Wales, and traditional Welsh folk music is often played on this harp.

46:25.520 --> 46:32.880
My grandfather was in a choir, Owen told Ben. He told me that the first time he left his village

46:32.880 --> 46:40.000
was when he was 23, when his choir sang in a competition in Cardiff. He used to tell me

46:40.000 --> 46:46.080
stories of his life in the village. He said that when he was a boy, choirs were a natural part

46:46.080 --> 46:54.000
of village life. I can still hear his voice saying, When I was a lad, you did what your father did.

46:54.000 --> 47:00.560
You left school, got a job in the mines, and became a member of a choir. That's how it was in the

47:00.560 --> 47:09.200
village. Wales in films and TV The Welsh countryside is a great location for films,

47:09.200 --> 47:15.760
because it has an interesting and diverse landscape, beautiful long coasts, high mountains,

47:15.760 --> 47:22.880
and magnificent cliffs. In Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows, there is a scene when Harry and

47:22.880 --> 47:29.440
his friends hide in Dobby's Shell Cottage. This cottage was built especially for the film

47:29.440 --> 47:35.840
on the sandy beach of Pembroksha, West Wales. Although the cottage isn't there anymore,

47:35.840 --> 47:41.440
you can still walk along the beach and imagine you are walking with Harry, Hermione and Ron.

47:42.480 --> 47:51.120
In 2010, this same location was chosen for the film Robin Hood. This time, it was used to present

47:51.120 --> 47:57.280
a ferocious battle. Horsemen dressed in armour and with flags in their hands galloped along the

47:57.280 --> 48:04.240
beach. The main actor, Russell Crow, liked the location so much that he camped on the sand for

48:04.240 --> 48:08.560
several nights instead of flying back to his luxurious hotel in London.

48:09.920 --> 48:16.240
American actress Kristin Stewart was also fascinated by the beautiful Pembroksha sands

48:16.240 --> 48:24.080
when she played Snow White in the film Snow White and the Huntsman 2012. There is an exciting

48:24.080 --> 48:30.000
scene in which Snow White rides with 80 men on horseback, and this was filmed along Marlowe's

48:30.000 --> 48:38.320
sands in Pembroksha. Doctor Who? Doctor Who is a British science fiction television series

48:38.320 --> 48:48.800
which began in 1963 and continued until 1989. It was later revived in 2005 due to popular demand.

48:49.600 --> 48:55.360
The series is about a doctor who travels in time in his special time travel machine,

48:55.360 --> 49:02.800
the TARDIS. The series is filmed in South Wales. For tourists who like sands fiction,

49:02.800 --> 49:09.760
filming and technology, a visit to the Doctor Who experience in Cardiff Bay is a must. There,

49:09.760 --> 49:16.160
they can learn about the filming of Doctor Who and see many of the different props like the TARDIS,

49:16.160 --> 49:22.000
the monsters and the costumes that appear in the series. They can also discover how they

49:22.000 --> 49:28.160
create the amazing special effects. It's a very interesting and popular attraction.

49:29.440 --> 49:32.320
Chapter 12 Wales Today

49:33.840 --> 49:40.240
Tourism In the past, coal and slate mining were the main industries in Wales.

49:40.880 --> 49:48.560
But today, the main industry is tourism, with over 8 million visitors a year. Most of the

49:48.560 --> 49:54.720
tourists come from other parts of the United Kingdom, especially England. Wales also attracts

49:54.720 --> 50:01.760
tourists from the United States and Europe, particularly France and Germany. Visiting the

50:01.760 --> 50:08.000
numerous castles and other historic sites is a popular activity for tourists, especially in the

50:08.000 --> 50:14.560
summer, when you can watch representations of battles and jousting. Wales is a wonderful

50:14.560 --> 50:20.800
country to visit if you like the outdoor life. The most popular tourist activities are climbing

50:20.800 --> 50:28.320
in the mountains and other sports, such as canoeing and cycling. But if you like more of a challenge,

50:28.320 --> 50:35.440
there's also hangliding or downhill mountain biking. There are over 1 million Americans of

50:35.440 --> 50:41.440
Welsh descent, so many of them come to discover their origins and learn about their ancestors,

50:41.440 --> 50:47.920
culture and traditions. Wales also has got some beautiful and unusual

50:47.920 --> 50:55.680
glamping sites. Glamping means glamorous camping. Not everyone enjoys the normal camping

50:55.680 --> 51:02.240
experience, sleeping bags, tents, fires or worrying about keeping their things dry when it rains.

51:03.040 --> 51:08.160
When you go glamping, you can enjoy the positive experiences of being outdoors,

51:08.160 --> 51:14.960
but with every comfort, like beds, bathrooms and heating. There are all kinds of Welsh

51:14.960 --> 51:22.480
glamping sites, tree houses, cabins and tents. Some are more luxurious than others, but they're

51:22.480 --> 51:32.560
all very comfortable. Fashion Wales has got many sheep, so it's not surprising that wool has played

51:32.560 --> 51:39.120
an important part in Welsh industry throughout the years. In fact, spinning and weaving of wool

51:39.120 --> 51:44.800
already existed in prehistoric times. The production of wooling whales was a very important

51:44.800 --> 51:51.200
industry in the country until World War I. Today, there are only a few wool mills,

51:51.200 --> 51:57.200
and these are usually operated by small families. They still produce traditional Welsh cloth

51:57.200 --> 52:04.400
using old looms, protecting the environment. Like other countries,

52:04.400 --> 52:10.000
Wales is looking for ways to protect the environment and reduce carbon dioxide emissions.

52:10.880 --> 52:18.560
One solution is building a wind farm to produce electricity. Wind power doesn't consume fuel,

52:18.560 --> 52:25.280
and it doesn't generate air pollution. Gwinter moor is an example of an offshore wind farm.

52:25.920 --> 52:31.840
It's off the coast of North Wales, and it's the second largest offshore wind farm in the world.

52:32.560 --> 52:40.160
It has 160 wind turbines that can produce enough energy for approximately 30% of homes in Wales.

52:41.600 --> 52:42.960
Welsh independence

52:45.040 --> 52:50.720
Some Welsh people prefer to maintain their national identity without leaving the United

52:50.720 --> 52:57.280
Kingdom. But there are other Welsh people who want independence, and certainly more control

52:57.280 --> 53:03.360
over decisions that affect their lives. There are political parties who want Welsh independence

53:03.360 --> 53:10.400
from the United Kingdom. One of the main parties that promotes this ideology is the Welsh nationalist

53:10.400 --> 53:18.160
party, Plaid Company. In the early 20th century, there was a fear among many Welsh people that

53:18.240 --> 53:22.800
their language and culture would disappear as English became the official language.

53:23.760 --> 53:31.360
As a result, Plaid Company was founded in 1925. One of its main objectives was to create a

53:31.360 --> 53:38.960
bilingual society by reviving the Welsh language. It also wanted to promote Wales' contribution

53:38.960 --> 53:44.080
in the global market, as well as to become a member of the United Nations.

53:45.040 --> 53:51.280
The recent vote for Great Britain to exit from the European Union, Brexit, has raised the question

53:51.280 --> 53:58.560
of Welsh independence. Most Welsh people voted to leave the European Union, and Plaid Company's

53:58.560 --> 54:04.160
leader sees Brexit as an opportunity for Wales to become an independent country.

54:05.840 --> 54:12.080
Many Welsh people may disagree about independence, but most of them want to promote Welsh identity

54:12.080 --> 54:17.760
and language throughout Wales today. The Welsh are proud of their country,

54:17.760 --> 54:22.560
their traditions, and their contribution to all areas of British life.

54:42.880 --> 54:48.080
He lived with his master, William Thomas, in the coastal city of Swansea.

54:49.120 --> 54:55.760
He became famous for saving people from the sea. When Swansea Jack heard a cry of help,

54:55.760 --> 55:03.040
he dived into the cold water and pulled the person to a safe place. His first rescue was in June

55:03.040 --> 55:10.240
1931, when he was only a year old. He jumped into the sea and saved a 12-year-old boy.

55:11.200 --> 55:16.080
Nobody knew what he had done until a few weeks later when he rescued another swimmer.

55:16.800 --> 55:22.880
This time, a crowd of people saw his actions, and his photograph appeared in the local newspaper.

55:23.840 --> 55:31.120
Then, news of his first rescue became known. According to legend, he saved 27 people in his

55:31.120 --> 55:39.280
lifetime. In fact, Swansea Jack saved so many people that he won the bravest dog of the year award,

55:39.360 --> 55:44.880
a silver collar, a silver cup from the Lord Mayor of London, and two bronze medals.

55:45.920 --> 55:52.080
Dog lovers enjoyed meeting Swansea Jack, and he often appeared at carnivals and shows with his

55:52.080 --> 56:00.880
owner to help raise money for charity. Sadly, Swansea Jack died in 1937 after eating rat poison.

56:01.520 --> 56:06.960
The people of Swansea were so proud of their dog that they built a special monument to him,

56:06.960 --> 56:10.720
which visitors can see today near Swansea's rugby ground.

56:11.440 --> 56:13.280
Page 60, Rollo

56:14.000 --> 56:19.440
When people go to agricultural shows, they usually see sheep dogs hurting animals.

56:20.160 --> 56:25.680
But for several years, the star of these shows in Wales and other places in the UK

56:25.680 --> 56:34.080
was a woolly white sheep called Rollo. Welsh farmer Emlim Roberts became Rollo's owner in 2005.

56:34.880 --> 56:39.360
He rescued her on a visit to friends when she was a tiny lamb in Canavan.

56:40.320 --> 56:45.680
Everyone thought the lamb had died, he said, but then he saw she was still alive,

56:45.680 --> 56:52.640
so he decided to take her home. The little lamb recovered and Emlim called her Rollo because her

56:52.640 --> 56:59.600
favourite treat was a famous British chocolate sweet called Rollo. Rollo grew up with Emlim's

56:59.680 --> 57:05.600
sheep dogs and it became obvious she thought she was also a dog because she started to behave

57:05.600 --> 57:11.120
like them. She ate her meals with them and suttered Emlim's feet while he watched TV.

57:12.080 --> 57:17.440
But Emlim was even more surprised when she started to copy the dogs and bring his ducks

57:17.440 --> 57:24.720
together and into their pen for the night. In 2006, he started to take her to agricultural shows

57:24.800 --> 57:30.640
and amazed the crowds with her talents. Besides herding ducks around a special course,

57:30.640 --> 57:38.000
she jumped over fences and did other tricks too. Sadly, Rollo died in 2013,

57:38.000 --> 57:43.280
but Emlim is now training Rollo's nephew, Horlix, to do tricks and dance.

57:44.320 --> 57:54.560
Emlim hopes the people will love him the same way they loved Rollo.

